{
  "answer": "The passage occurs in *San Hyan Mahajnana*, Chapter 1.[^1]\n\nThe verse (verse 58) is:  \n\"*Let the fool speak thus, [...] the gall bladder [...]. Of the measure of the seven islands, the king becomes powerful. // 58* \"[^2]\n\nThe subsequent prose gloss, framing the 'great fool'/'pandit' debate on the gall bladder's size (thumb's breadth vs. the size of the seven islands), reads verbatim:  \n\"Now, as for the gall bladder, its measure is that of a thumb. [...] Where is this great fool, who argues about its nature? It is said that the gall bladder is a thumb’s breadth in size. The gall bladder is as large as the seven islands. What are the seven islands? Such is the Lord Īśvara; He is of great power, all-pervading. Thus are the words of the fool. This is what is called the argument of a pandit.\"[^1]\n\n[^1]: *San Hyan Mahajnana*, [Chapter 1](/works/unknown-san-hyan-mahajnana-11c531/01/translation/#p-371134).\n\n[^2]: *San Hyan Mahajnana*, [verse 58](/works/unknown-san-hyan-mahajnana-11c531/01/translation/#p-a0c6ba).",
